cs.DS, cs.PL, cs.SE, cs.DC, cs.AL

Reasoning: 
- cs.DS (Data Structures and Algorithms): The paper presents a new algorithm for Quicksort and compares it to other well-known implementations. This is a core topic in data structures and algorithms.
- cs.PL (Programming Languages): The paper provides both a pointer-based and an array-based implementation of the algorithm, which can be easily ported to different programming languages. This is relevant to the field of programming languages.
- cs.SE (Software Engineering): The paper presents an industrial-grade implementation of Quicksort, which is meant as a replacement for the C/C++ library qsort(). This is relevant to the field of software engineering.
- cs.DC (Distributed, Parallel, and Cluster Computing): The paper does not explicitly mention distributed, parallel, or cluster computing, but the performance improvements of the new algorithm could potentially be relevant to these fields.
- cs.AL (Computational Complexity): The paper discusses the number of comparisons and swaps required by different Quicksort implementations, which is related to the computational complexity of the algorithm.
